		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Pulley</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For the band, see <a href="/wiki/Pulley_(band)" title="Pulley (band)">Pulley (band)</a>. For the village, see <a href="/wiki/Pulley,_Shropshire" title="Pulley, Shropshire">Pulley, Shropshire</a>. For the American photographer, see <a href="/wiki/Gerald_P._Pulley" title="Gerald P. Pulley">Gerald P. Pulley</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:PulleyShip.JPG" class="image" title="Pulleys on a ship. In this context, pulleys are usually known as blocks."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/PulleyShip.JPG/180px-PulleyShip.JPG" width="180" height="135" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:PulleyShip.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Pulleys on a ship. In this context, pulleys are usually known as <a href="/wiki/Block_(sailing)" title="Block (sailing)">blocks</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A <b>pulley</b> (also called a <b>block</b>) is a mechanism composed of a <a href="/wiki/Wheel" title="Wheel">wheel</a> (called a <b>sheave</b>) with a <a href="/wiki/Groove_(machining)" title="Groove (machining)">groove</a> between two <a href="/wiki/Flange" title="Flange">flanges</a> around the wheel's <a href="/wiki/Circumference" title="Circumference">circumference</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Rope" title="Rope">rope</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cable" title="Cable">cable</a> or <a href="/wiki/Belt_(mechanical)" title="Belt (mechanical)">belt</a> usually runs inside the groove. Pulleys are used to change the direction of an applied <a href="/wiki/Force" title="Force">force</a>, transmit rotational motion, or realize a <a href="/wiki/Mechanical_advantage" title="Mechanical advantage">mechanical advantage</a> in either a linear or rotational system of motion.</p>
